  "topic_name": "Magnetism",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "A magnet is an object that attracts magnetic materials like iron, cobalt, and nickel. Every magnet has two poles - North (N) and South (S). Like poles repel each other while unlike poles attract. The region around a magnet where its magnetic effect is felt is called the magnetic field. Magnetic field lines show the direction and strength of the magnetic field, going from North to South outside the magnet. An electromagnet is a temporary magnet created by passing electric current through a coil wound around an iron core. Electromagnets have many applications including electric bells, cranes, and speakers.",
    "rules": [
      "Magnets attract iron, cobalt, nickel (magnetic materials).",
      "Every magnet has North and South poles.",
      "Like poles repel; unlike poles attract.",
      "Magnetic field: region around magnet where effect is felt.",
      "Field lines go from N to S outside the magnet.",
      "Electromagnet: temporary magnet made using current.",
      "Electromagnet strength increases with more turns and stronger current.",
      "Freely suspended magnet points North-South."
    ]
  },
